g1009470-d547439	Talia G	Bat Yam, Israel	122	5.0	5	October	2021	Oct	2021	Fun, challenging adventure in wonderful nature	Couples	We chose to explore this canyon as our one day experience of the Slovak Paradise National Park, and it’s definitely a hike we will remember! We came on a Monday in the first week of October l and were fortunate to experience a gorgeously sunny day. We parked in Podlesok - there are 2 lots, the slightly closer lot is paid by app, so we went to Parking Zone 2 where we paid a park ranger 3 euros for the full day of parking, and the entry fee which is 1.50euro per person. As it was a weekday it was very empty, but we could tell on the weekend this is a popular place to visit and you should arrive early (we got there around 10:30). At Podlesok there are several lodges/restaurants, and some places offering bike rentals for about 30 euros each — again as it was a Monday everything seemed to be closed. *Disclaimer* I did this hike at 7 months pregnant with a patient husband. We normally love hiking, and would consider ourselves in relatively good shape. But the timings listed on the signs definitely seem to be aimed toward the fitter hikers and not average in slower walkers. In all, we did a 15km hike in 5.5 hours (with a 20 minute rest break at the top). We started off on the blue trail which took us along the canyon (Prielom Hornadu). It’s about 1km from the parking lot until you actually get into the park, passing by some lodges and auto camping. After the first bridge there is another park ranger who checks to make sure you have a ticket. From there the adventure begins. The climb is relatively flat - any uphill climbs are short and aided by metal steps/ladders and chains. At first, they can appear intimidating as hell, but after the first round you get the hang of it and it was very fun (except one stretch which is directly over the water! That was a little stomach turning). It’s a challenging hike, often narrow, and you have to focus on where to place your feet as you climb over tree roots and rocks. But it’s pristine nature, you can feel the cold air coming off the water, and it was silent given how few people were out that day. The canyon is 16 km long, so we started to loop at marker number 5 and climb toward Klastorisko. You can choose the green or yellow trail up - the green is just slightly longer and involves a 5m ladder up the side of the cascade. We consulted with another couple, locals who seemed to be familiar with the path, and she made a face when I said I was pregnant, so we went with the yellow trail. It was no joke! In total you ascend 220 meters, incredibly narrow and steep, with considerably fewer rope chains or steps than in the canyon. There was not much to see either along this route. When we finally made it into the glen we continued on for at least 500 meters or more until making it to a medieval site that had some ruins and a cemetery (I joked to my husband that it was convenient for him to just bury me here, as I was absolutely dead after that climb). There did appear to be a lodge that might be open on weekends to offer some refreshment, but you should definitely pack some food. It took about 3 hours to do this stretch of canyon and climb. Going down was close to another 2 hours. We combined the green, then yellow, then red trails to take us back down to the car. These paths offer a wide bicycle route which is a slightly gravely path marked by “C” that winds down at a manageable slope. There is also a narrow walking path that is more of a straight shot down, but it’s steep and has you clambering over rocks and roots. There is a lot of ground water so it can often get slippery, you definitely need hiking shoes. It was a fantastic hike that leaves you feeling sore and exhilarated.	d8bc4b69-e214-2fdd-dac9-6f8c4833ea83	{nl, -45.11754608154297}	{en, -9295.148480415344}	{en:0.8571374256063037, nl:0.1428589866770838}	{en:0.9999951611605453}	We chose to explore this canyon as our one d