g277810-d4312850	Dansnd	Mengusovce, Slovakia	40	4.0	12	June	2013	May	2013	Belianska Cave	Family	This is a fairly short tour of a cave system (about an hour). It isn't too demanding but cave tours mean a lot of steps so not for the very old. In general the commentary is in Slovak but they will make an effort to add some English if they know there are foreign visitors. Like most caves, it is pretty cool inside (about 7 C I believe) so dress well. The cave is not open all year (just late spring to early Autumn I think) and there are set times with quite an early finish so check the times before you arrive. There is a large sign at the bottom of the footpath which leads up to the cave, make sure you check that the cave is open before you go up, the path takes 10-15 minutes of 'healthy exercise' as you wind your way up. Having got to the top you find that they do not take credit cards so make sure you have enough cash. You have to wait for the next tour as people cannot just wander around in the cave, just as part of a tour group. Make sure you check your watches are correct by looking at the clock at the ticket office ;-) The cave is lit and the paths are fairly good but obviously damp and not level so good footwear is a must. There are bats in there but not many and you will have to look hard to find them. Taller people should be careful as headroom is limited in some places and you can easily bump your head. Overall, it is worth seeing if you are in the area or passing through but I wouldn't travel to see it. There are far more impressive cave systems near Jasna or towards Roznava.  There is a good Slovak restaurant next to the car park. As well as being an interesting place (it looks like a museum of an old style cottage), its car park is free so having a coffee there is better than paying for the Cave car park in my opinion. The food is good and inexpensive so we usually eat there too. Arrange your eating time to fit in with the cave tour times - having a long lunch